**Session \- 03 \- Golang Setup**

1. Golang Installation  
   1. Install Golang  
2. **Setting Go**  
   1. Setting `GOROOT`  
      1. Run command `which go`  
         1. It may say something like `/usr/local/go/bin/go`  
      2. Run command `echo $GOROOT`  
         1. Based on the response of point 1, this should refer to `/usr/local/go`  
         2. Notice this is the first part for `which go`  
   2. Setting `GOPATH`  
      1. Run command `echo $GOPATH` and check the response.  
         1. It should have a response like   
            1. `/Users/<your system login user>/go`  
         2. Remember the folder structure we had used in **Session-02**  
            ![][image1]  
      2. \* This `GOPATH` should refer to **workspace** folder  
   3. If these env vars are not referring the correct values:  
      1. Go to your home folder  
      2. Create/edit a file by name `.zshrc`  
      3. The contents should be something like:  
         1. export GOROOT=/usr/local/go  
         2. export GOBIN=$GOPATH/bin  
         3. export GOPATH=$HOME/go  
      4. Once this is done, exit the terminal and re-open the terminal  
         1. Now check all the above env vars

***Note:*** 

3. *For each of your program do the following*

   2. *Create the program and ensure it is working*  
   3. *Ensure to merge your code in **your GitHub** repo, under **development** branch*

4. **Program 01**  
   1. Create a go program to print “Hello World”  
5. **Program 02**  
   1. Create a program to read all Golang related environment variables and print them  
   2. Understand how package is imported  
6. **Program 03**  
   1. Create a main.go and main function to print "Starting Program03”  
   2. Create another file by name helper.go, under **main** package  
      1. In this file create a function which reads and prints the env vars, as done in **program 02**  
   3. Call this function from main function  
   4. Run the program from terminal and get it working  
7. **Program 04**  
   1. Create a main function and try to generate a new UUID every time program is executed  
   2. Observe all the files in the project explorer  
   3. Execute command **go mod init**  
   4. Observe the files in the project structure  
   5. You will notice a new file go.mod  
   6. Open it and check what it contains  
      1. Try to understand everything this file contains  
   7. Execute command **go mod tidy**  
   8. You will notice another new file go.sum  
   9. Open this file and try to understand all its content  
8. **Program 05**  
   1. Copy **program 04** as **program 05**  
   2. Modify this program as follows  
      1. Accept some text as command line argument  
      2. Generate sha256 for the argument and print  
9. Run each of the above program in debug mode through the editor  
   1. Programs where external packages are used, try to step-in to the function  
   2. Try to debug those packages also.  
      1. You can limit up to depth of 2 to 3 level  
      2. At the moment any more depth is not required  
   3. When you step in, notice the file which gets opened, and where this file is stored in your system   
10. **Sample program to Clone and get it running.**  
    1. **Note:**  
       1. This exercise is only to practice how to get a repository working.  
       2. At this moment we are not interested in what the code is all about  
       3. Our focus is on how to get a repository/code working.  
       4. Definition of working:  
          1. The main function should start working.  
          2. It may throw some error indicating how to use the tool, which is ok  
          3. Once you reach this stage, you will have experienced the process of getting a code running on your local system  
    2. **Exercise:**  
       1. On your local system, under github.com folder create a folder by name **opensbom-generator**  
       2. Inside the folder **opensbom-generator**, clone the following repository  
          1. [https://github.com/opensbom-generator/spdx-sbom-generator](https://github.com/opensbom-generator/spdx-sbom-generator)  
       3. Notice we have created a folder similar to **github org/user** of the git repository.  
       4. Open the code in an editor  
       5. Notice many of the imports will be shown as error/not found  
       6. Ensure to resolve all the import errors.  
       7. Ensure the following 2 main functions can be built  
          1. cmd/generator/generator.go  
          2. cmd/sbomgen/[sbomgen.go](http://sbomgen.go)  
       8. Try to study go.mod and go.sum files  
          1. Example entry in go.mod:  
             1. github.com/google/uuid v1.2.0  
          2. Try to go the repository [github.com/google/uuid](http://github.com/google/uuid)  
          3. Understand the meaning of v1.2.0  
       9. Try to explore other go.mod entries  
       10. **Expectation:**  
           1. At the end of this study you should understand what is the meaning of importing a library in a go project
